04489nam a22007215i 9780292769755DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927697557 a10.7560/7081812doi  a(DE-B1597)588743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF2520.1.A63bB366 1995 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a398.2/09812201 aBasso, Ellen B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Last Cannibals :bA South American Oral History /cEllen B. Basso. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tA GUIDE TO PRONOUNCING KALAPALO WORDS -- tPART 1 -- tCHAPTER 1 Introduction -- tCHAPTER 2 The Language in Storytelling -- tCHAPTER 3 An Early Experience of Europeans Told by Muluku -- tCHAPTER 4 Kambe's Testimony -- tPART 2 -- tCHAPTER 5 Warriors -- tCHAPTER 6 Ahpiu's Story about Wapagepundaka -- tCHAPTER 7 Madyuta's Story about Tapoge -- tCHAPTER 8 Kudyu's Story about Tamakafi -- tPART 3 -- tCHAPTER 9 Kudyu's Story of the Wanderers -- tCHAPTER 10 Ausuki Tells of the Trumai People -- tCHAPTER 11 Ugaki Tells of Afuseti, a Woman Stolen by Angikogo -- tCHAPTER 12 Tsangaku Tells of the Dyaguma -- tPART 4 -- tCHAPTER 13 Conclusion: History, Ideology, and the Personal Version of Reality -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX OF STORIES -- tGENERAL INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn especially comprehensive study of Brazilian Amazonian Indian history, The Last Cannibals is the first attempt to understand, through indigenous discourse, the emergence of Upper Xingú society. Drawing on oral documents recorded directly from the native language, Ellen Basso transcribes and analyzes nine traditional Kalapalo stories to offer important insights into Kalapalo historical knowledge and the performance of historical narratives within their nonliterate society. This engaging book challenges the familiar view of biography as a strictly Western literary form. Of special interest are biographies of powerful warriors whose actions led to the emergence of a more recent social order based on restrained behaviors from an earlier time when people were said to be fierce and violent. From these stories, Basso explores how the Kalapalo remember and understand their past and what specific linguistic, psychological, and ideological materials they employ to construct their historical consciousness. Her book will be important reading in anthropology, folklore, linguistics, and South American studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aApalakiri Indians -- Folklore. 0aApalakiri Indians -- History. 0aApalakiri IndiansvFolklore. 0aApalakiri IndiansxHistory. 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative -- Brazil -- Xingu River Valley. 0aDiscourse analysis, NarrativezBrazilzXingu River Valley. 0aEthnohistory -- Brazil -- Xingu River Valley. 0aEthnohistoryzBrazilzXingu River Valley. 0aOral tradition -- Brazil -- Xingu River Valley. 0aOral traditionzBrazilzXingu River Valley. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70818140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769755/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK